name: I've a Shooting Box in Scotland
comments: The first Porter song to have a commercial recording, when Joseph C. Smith and his orchestra recorded it in 1917. It has lasted in the repertoire of Porter's songs as a witty patter song. It was introduced in 1914 in the Yale production Paranoia by Newbold Noyes and Rufus F. King and   appeared with revised lyric in the 1916 Broadway show See America First , where it was performed by Dorothie Bigelow and John Heath Goldsworthy. There is a fairly well-known parody called "Shooting Pains in Scotland." Porter himself may have written the lyrics to the parody, as he often referred to the song as "Shooting Pains in Scotland."
